## Design notes

### Why this is a true sliding window

| Fixed window | Sliding window (this implementation) |
|---|---|
| Resets counter at `t = 0, 60, 120…` | Looks back exactly `windowMs` from **now**, every request |
| A burst at `t=59s` + another at `t=61s` = two full quotas in 2 s | The same burst is counted together — no seam to exploit |
| `O(1)` per request | `O(log n)` per request (binary-search prune) — negligible in practice |

### Header semantics

| Header | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `X-RateLimit-Limit` | The configured `maxRequests` ceiling |
| `X-RateLimit-Remaining` | Slots left in the current window **after** this request |
| `X-RateLimit-Reset` | Unix epoch seconds when the **oldest** in-window request expires and a slot opens |
| `Retry-After` | (429 only) Seconds until the first slot frees — ceiling-rounded so clients don't retry a millisecond too early |

### Memory & cleanup

- Each allowed request appends one 8-byte number to the IP's array; rejected requests touch nothing.
- The cleanup interval sweeps the entire map every `cleanupIntervalMs` and deletes any IP whose window is now empty, bounding memory to **active clients × window depth**.
- `cleanupTimer.unref()` marks the timer as non-blocking so it won't keep a test process alive after your server closes. Call `close()` during graceful shutdown for an explicit clear.

### Proxy / `req.ip` caveat

Without `app.set('trust proxy', …)`, `req.ip` is the socket's remote address — your proxy's IP. Every client would share one rate-limit bucket. The safest production setting is `trust proxy: 1` (trust exactly one upstream hop). Avoid `trust proxy: true`; it accepts any `X-Forwarded-For` value, letting a client inject a fake IP and completely bypass the limiter.

